SIMPLE: spit
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spite</ets>,
AS. <ets>spitu</ets>; akin to D. <ets>spit</ets>, G. <ets>spiess</ets>,
OHG. <ets>spiz</ets>, Dan. <ets>spid</ets>. Sw. <ets>spett</ets>, and to
G. <ets>spitz</ets> pointed. ⟦root⟧170.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A long,
slender, pointed rod, usually of iron, for holding meat while
roasting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small point of land running into the sea, or a
long, narrow shoal extending from the shore into the sea; <as>as, a
<ex>spit</ex> of sand</as>.</def> <rj><au>Cook.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The depth to which a spade goes in digging; a spade;
a spadeful.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Spit</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>; cf. <er>Speet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To thrust a
spit through; to fix upon a spit; hence, to thrust through or impale;
<as>as, to <ex>spit</ex> a loin of veal</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Infants
<xex>spitted</xex> upon pikes.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spade; to dig.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To attend to a spit; to use a
spit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She's <qex>spitting</qex> in the kitchen.</q> <rj><qau>Old
Play.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spit</conjf> (<conjf>Spat</conjf>, <mark>archaic</mark>); <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Spitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>spittan</ets>; akin to G. <ets>sp⟦uum⟧tzen</ets>, Dan.
<ets>spytte</ets>, Sw. <ets>spotta</ets>,Icel. <ets>sp<?/ta</ets>, and
prob. E. <ets>spew</ets>. The past tense <ets>spat</ets> is due to AS.
<ets>sp<?/tte</ets>, from <ets>sp<?/tan</ets> to spit. Cf.
<er>Spat</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Spew</er>, <er>Spawl</er>,
<er>Spot</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To eject from the
mouth; to throw out, as saliva or other matter, from the mouth.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Thus <xex>spit</xex> I out my venom.⟦rdquo⟧ <-- spat is a common
pp and not archaic --> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To eject; to throw out; to belch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Spitted</xex> was sometimes used as the preterit
and the past participle. ⟦ldquo⟧He . . . shall be mocked, and spitefully
entreated, and <xex>spitted</xex> on.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Luke xviii.
32.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The secretion formed by the glands of
the mouth; spitle; saliva; sputum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Spit
<hw>Spit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw out saliva
from the mouth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rain or snow slightly, or with
sprinkles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It had been <qex>spitting</qex> with rain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To spit on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To spit
upon</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to insult grossly; to treat with
contempt.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Spitting upon</xex> all antiquity.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>South.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spital</ent>⟦br⟧
